🧠 Minimum Absolute Difference in Sliding Submatrix
🔹 Intuition

For any k × k submatrix, we only care about:

minimum difference between any two distinct values

Key observation:
👉 Minimum absolute difference will always be between closest elements after sorting
So instead of checking all pairs (O(n²)):
→ just sort / keep ordered structure
→ check adjacent differences only
🔹 Approach (Brute but Optimized Enough)
For each submatrix:
Collect all elements
Store in sorted structure (set)
If only 1 unique element → answer = 0
Else:
Traverse sorted set
Take min of (current - previous)
🔹 Code (Your Approach - Clean)
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> minAbsDiff(vector<vector<int>>& grid, int k) {
        int m = grid.size();
        int n = grid[0].size();
        
        vector<vector<int>> ans(m-k+1, vector<int>(n-k+1));

        for(int i = 0; i <= m-k; i++) {
            for(int j = 0; j <= n-k; j++) {

                set<int> st;

                // collect elements of submatrix
                for(int x = i; x < i + k; x++) {
                    for(int y = j; y < j + k; y++) {
                        st.insert(grid[x][y]);
                    }
                }

                // compute min diff
                int diff = INT_MAX;

                if(st.size() == 1) diff = 0;
                else {
                    for(auto it = next(st.begin()); it != st.end(); it++) {
                        diff = min(diff, *it - *prev(it));
                    }
                }

                ans[i][j] = diff;
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
🔹 Complexity
Submatrices: O((m-k+1)*(n-k+1))
Each submatrix:
Insert: O(k² log k²)
Traverse: O(k²)

👉 Overall:

~ O(m * n * k² log k)

✔ Works because constraints small (≤ 30)

🔹 Key Tricks 💡
❌ Don't check all pairs
✅ Only check adjacent in sorted order
set automatically maintains sorted order
🔹 Better Options (Optimization Ideas)
1. Use Vector + Sort instead of set
Faster in practice (less overhead)
vector<int> v;
for(...) v.push_back(...);

sort(v.begin(), v.end());

for(int i = 1; i < v.size(); i++)
    diff = min(diff, v[i] - v[i-1]);

👉 Same logic, faster constant

2. Sliding Window + Multiset (Advanced ❗)
Instead of rebuilding every time:
Remove left column
Add right column

👉 But:

Hard to maintain min diff dynamically
Not worth it for constraints
3. Frequency Array (if constraints small)
Not applicable here (range too large: ±1e5)
🔹 Final Take

👉 This problem is about:

recognizing "min diff ⇒ adjacent after sorting"
brute force is acceptable due to small constraints
